cutemany(\"INSERT INTO jobs (...) VALUES (:key, ...)\", insert_rows)\n    if update_rows:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET ... WHERE key=:key\", update_rows)\n    if unchanged_keys:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", [(now, k) for k in unchanged_keys])\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n`existing.get(...)` requires `row_factory` back to tuples for that query, or index `[1]`/`[\"content_hash\"]` тАФ adjust to taste. This turns O(N) statement executions into O(N/500 + 3).\n\n## 2. Redundant computation тАФ regex recompiled per job (`filters.py:11-27`)\n\n`_compile()` is called on every call to `match()`, and `match()` is called once per job inside `filter_jobs`. For M keyword patterns and N jobs, you compile the same M patterns N times.\n\n```python\ndef match(job: Job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...):\n    if exclude:\n        if any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(exclude)):  # recompiled every job!\n```\n\n**Fix** тАФ compile once in `filter_jobs` and pass compiled patterns down:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    include_re = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude_re = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    cutoff = ...\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include_re, exclude=exclude_re, ...)]\n```\nand drop the `_compile()` calls out of `match()`. For a few hundred jobs ├Ч a handful of keywords this is cheap, but it's pure waste тАФ free to fix.\n\n## 3. Redundant computation тАФ `Job.content_hash`/`key` recomputed multiple times (`models.py:55-69`)\n\nBoth are plain `@property`, so every access recomputes (sha256 + string join for the hash, an f-string for the key). In `Store.diff()`, `job.key` is read at least twice and `job.content_hash` is read once for comparison and again inside `to_row()` тАФ a redundant sha256 per job.\n\n**Fix** тАФ cache with `functools.cached_property` (works fine on a `slots=True` dataclass if you add `\"_key_cache\"`/reserve a slot, or simpler: compute once in `to_row()` and reuse):\n\n```python\ndef to_row(self) -> dict[str, Any]:\n    d = asdict(self)\n    d.pop(\"raw\", None)\n    key, hash_ = self.key, self.content_hash  # compute once\n    d[\"key\"], d[\"content_hash\"] = key, hash_\n    return d\n```\nThen in `Store.diff`, compute `job.key`/`job.content_hash` once per job into locals instead of re-reading the property.\n\n## 4. Caching opportunity тАФ missing index for `added_since` (`store.py:127-135`)\n\n```python\nreturn self.conn.execute(\n    \"SELECT * FROM jobs WHERE first_seen > ? ORDER BY first_seen, company, title\", (ts,)).fetchall()\n```\nThere's an index on `company` but none on `first_seen`, and this is the exact query `agent.py db-new` runs on every scan. It's a full table scan + filesort today; harmless at a few thousand rows but will degrade as `jobs.db` grows unboundedly (nothing ever purges old rows).\n\n**Fix**:\n```sql\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_jobs_first_seen ON jobs(first_seen);\n```\nAdd to `_SCHEMA` in `store.py`.\n\n## 5. Blocking I/O inside async pipeline тАФ `notify.py`\n\n`dispatch()` (`notify.py:105-110`) is called synchronously from inside `async def run()` (`pipeline.py:44`), and `notify_slack`/`notify_webhook`/`notify_sms` all use the **synchronous** `httpx.post`. Each call blocks the event loop thread for the full round trip (up to the 15s timeout), and each opens a brand-new TCP/TLS connection тАФ three separate connection setups for three notifiers that could share a client.\n\n**Fix** тАФ use `httpx.AsyncClient` and await them, ideally concurrently:\n\n```python\nasync def dispatch(new: list[Job], changed: list[Job]) -> None:\n    notify_console(new, changed)  # cheap, keep sync\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient(timeout=15) as client:\n        results = await asyncio.gather(\n            notify_slack(client, new, changed),\n            notify_webhook(client, new, changed),\n            notify_sms(client, new, changed),\n            return_exceptions=True,\n        )\n    for fn, r in zip((notify_slack, notify_webhook, notify_sms), results):\n        if isinstance(r, Exception):\n            print(f\"  ! notifier {fn.__name__} failed: {r}\")\n```\nand update `pipeline.py:44` to `await dispatch(new, changed)`. Low-severity today since it's the very last step of the run, but it's a real latency add-on (3 sequential blocking HTTP calls) that async fixes for free.\n\n## Not applicable / no issue found\n\n- **React re-renders / memoization**: no frontend code in this repo.\n- **Classic memory leaks**: `httpx.AsyncClient` is properly closed in `fetch_all`'s `finally` (`fetchers.py:1016-1020`), and `Store` is always used via context manager. No unbounded in-memory accumulation beyond one run's job list, which is bounded by each fetcher's `max_pages` cap.\n- **`_extract_ds1`/`_apple_hydration` regex-per-call**: technically re-searched per page fetch, but Python's `re` module internally caches compiled patterns (up to 512), and these run at most `max_pages` times per source (тЙд40), not per-job тАФ not worth the churn to hand-optimize.\n\nPriority order if you want me to implement: #1 (real N+1, biggest win) тЖТ #2 (trivial, free) тЖТ #5 (only matters if notifiers get slow/flaky) тЖТ #3/#4 (micro, do opportunistically). Want me to make these changes?\n",
